                       <!-- -->
                       <div class="feed-shared-update-v2__description-wrapper mr2" style="" tabindex="-1">
                        <div class="feed-shared-inline-show-more-text feed-shared-update-v2__description feed-shared-inline-show-more-text--minimal-padding feed-shared-inline-show-more-text--2-lines" tabindex="-1">
                         <div class="update-components-text relative update-components-update-v2__commentary" dir="ltr">
                          <!-- -->
                          <span class="break-words tvm-parent-container">
                           <!-- -->
                           <span dir="ltr">
                            <!-- -->
                            “This event was more than a moment. It was a movement. And the job’s not finished.”
                            <!-- -->
                            <span>
                             <br/>
                            </span>
                            <span>
                             <br/>
                            </span>
                            <!-- -->
                            This February, four NIKE teammates immersed themselves in the “Path to Progress” event in Washington D.C., an inspiring celebration of the milestone fourth year of NIKE’s Black Community Commitment (BCC).
                            <span class="white-space-pre">
                            </span>
                            <span>
                             <br/>
                            </span>
                            <span>
                             <br/>
                            </span>
                            <!-- -->
                            One of them was the teammate quoted above:
                            <span class="white-space-pre">
                            </span>
                            <a class="app-aware-link" data-test-app-aware-link="" href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/ACoAABLWRHgBnqltWgtE8K1H72votu_SCyuplZY" target="_self">
                             <span>
                              <a class="ember-view" href="/in/nakiah/" id="ember1236">
                               <!-- -->
                               Nakiah Williams
                               <!-- -->
                              </a>
                             </span>
                            </a>
                            <!-- -->
                            , a Nike Athlete Experience (NAX) Trainer in New York City. Over two days, Williams had the opportunity to listen in on a series of panel conversations highlighting the work and impact of BCC grantees, participate in a special tour of the National Museum of African American History and Culture and more.
                            <!-- -->
                            <span>
                             <br/>
                            </span>
                            <span>
                             <br/>
                            </span>
                            <!-- -->
                            “The BCC is helping to create a new narrative for the Black Community,” says Williams. “As a Nike employee, and as a leader within our Black Employee Network, I live, work and volunteer in the same communities we’re serving through the BCC. We're working firsthand to create that same narrative for change. You can’t help but be inspired by our future when you’re surrounded by the fearless ones, the change agents and the storytellers from the BCC grantees and the Nike, Jordan, and Converse Social &amp; Community Impact teams.”
                            <!-- -->
                            <span>
                             <br/>
                            </span>
                            <span>
                             <br/>
                            </span>
                            <!-- -->
                            Learn more about the celebration — and the path ahead — at
                            <span class="white-space-pre">
                            </span>
                            <a class="app-aware-link" data-test-app-aware-link="" href="https://lnkd.in/gavMu67h" target="_self">
                             <!-- -->
                             https://lnkd.in/gavMu67h
                             <!-- -->
                            </a>
                            <span>
                             <br/>
                            </span>
                            <span>
                             <br/>

                          <button aria-expanded="false" aria-label="Open control menu for post by Nike" class="feed-shared-control-menu__trigger artdeco-button artdeco-button--tertiary artdeco-button--muted artdeco-button--1 artdeco-button--circle artdeco-dropdown__trigger artdeco-dropdown__trigger--placement-bottom ember-view" id="ember1547" tabindex="0" type="button">

                       <!-- -->
                       <div class="feed-shared-update-v2__description-wrapper mr2" style="" tabindex="-1">
                        <div class="feed-shared-inline-show-more-text feed-shared-update-v2__description feed-shared-inline-show-more-text--minimal-padding feed-shared-inline-show-more-text--3-lines" tabindex="-1">
                         <div class="update-components-text relative update-components-update-v2__commentary" dir="ltr">
                          <!-- -->
                          <span class="break-words tvm-parent-container">
                           <!-- -->
                           <span dir="ltr">
                            <!-- -->
                            Every year, one of NIKE, Inc.’s most important beliefs — that all kids should have the opportunity to play, regardless of background, gender or ability — comes to life right here on our WHQ campus.
                            <!-- -->
                            <span>
                             <br/>
                            </span>
                            <span>
                             <br/>
                            </span>
                            <!-- -->
                            Through Nike’s longtime partnership with Special Olympics Oregon (SOOR), we had the privilege of hosting the SOOR Games last weekend, an opportunity to help introduce sport to nearly 500 young athletes with intellectual disabilities while celebrating the joy of movement with them and their families. And just as many Nike employees show up as volunteers. The SOOR Games is one of the fastest -filled employee volunteer events at our company. For many, the experience is an all-time Nike highlight, including for
                            <span class="white-space-pre">
                            </span>
                            <a class="app-aware-link" data-test-app-aware-link="" href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/ACoAAB7b8SIByPq_Lvu-QzZ1iQ_FAR5WLqIf5jc" target="_self">
                             <span>
                              <a class="ember-view" href="/in/paige-la-flamme621/" id="ember1549">
                               <!-- -->
                               Paige La Flamme
                               <!-- -->
                              </a>
                             </span>
                            </a>
                            <!-- -->
                            , a Nike Business Operations and Planning Lead in Technology Management, who also Co-Chairs Nike’s Disability Network. La Flamme says it’s only fitting that Nike’s spirit of volunteerism is so strong at the event.
                            <span class="white-space-pre">
                            </span>
                            <span>
                             <br/>
                            </span>
                            <span>
                             <br/>
                            </span>
                            <!-- -->
                            “The Special Olympics Youth Games is one of my favorite days of the year,” says La Flamme. “As a previous Special Olympics Oregon Intern, this organization and most importantly, the athletes, have a special place in my heart. It's amazing to see the power of the Nike Community come together to celebrate and show the collective strength of disability and the importance of sport through this event.”
                            <!-- -->
                            <span>
                             <br/>
                            </span>
                            <span>
                             <br/>
                            </span>
                            <!-- -->
                            The SOOR Games are only one example of NIKE, Inc.’s commitment to support accessibility and disability. In honor of National Disability Employment Awareness Month, Nike’s Disability Employee Network will lead a number of events in October that highlight the company’s dedicated hiring programs and the ways in which Nike is increasing accessibility for employees of every background.
                            <!-- -->
                            <span>
                             <br/>
                            </span>
                            <span>
                             <br/>
                            </span>
                            <!-- -->
                            Learn more about Nike’s employee networks at
                            <span class="white-space-pre">
                            </span>
                            <a class="app-aware-link" data-test-app-aware-link="" href="https://lnkd.in/gcxyit3S" target="_self">
                             <!-- -->
                             https://lnkd.in/gcxyit3S
                             <!-- -->
                            </a>
                            <span>
                             <br/>
                            </span>
                            <span>
                             <br/>
                            </span>
                            <a class="app-aware-link" data-test-app-aware-link="" href="https://www.linkedin.com/feed/hashtag/?keywords=lifeatnike&amp;highlightedUpdateUrns=urn%3Ali%3Aactivity%3A7114693258500349953">
                             <span class="visually-hidden">
                              hashtag
                             </span>
                             <span>
                              <span aria-hidden="true">
                               #
                              </span>
                              LifeAtNike
                             </span>
                            </a>
                            <span class="white-space-pre">
                            </span>
                            <!-- -->

                            To mark World Engineering Day — a global recognition of the extraordinary minds shaping our future through innovation — we want to recognize our Nike engineers who work tirelessly to blend creativity with technical expertise to redefine sport and empower athletes worldwide.
                            <span class="white-space-pre">
                            </span>

                            <span class="white-space-pre">

                               <!-- -->

                            </a>
                            <span class="white-space-pre">
                            </span>

                            <span class="white-space-pre">
                            </span>
                            <a class="app-aware-link" data-test-app-aware-link="" href="https://www.linkedin.com/feed/hashtag/?keywords=worldengineeringday&amp;highlightedUpdateUrns=urn%3Ali%3Aactivity%3A7170524004276011008">

                          <button aria-expanded="false" aria-label="Open control menu for post by Nike" class="feed-shared-control-menu__trigger artdeco-button artdeco-button--tertiary artdeco-button--muted artdeco-button--1 artdeco-button--circle artdeco-dropdown__trigger artdeco-dropdown__trigger--placement-bottom ember-view" id="ember1641" tabindex="0" type="button">

                       <div class="feed-shared-update-v2__description-wrapper mr2" style="" tabindex="-1">
                        <div class="feed-shared-inline-show-more-text feed-shared-update-v2__description feed-shared-inline-show-more-text--minimal-padding feed-shared-inline-show-more-text--3-lines" tabindex="-1">
                         <div class="update-components-text relative update-components-update-v2__commentary" dir="ltr">
                          <!-- -->
                          <span class="break-words tvm-parent-container">
                           <!-- -->
                           <span dir="ltr">
                            <!-- -->
                            Nine major U.S. cities. Seventy-eight youth organizations. Two partners who share a common vision: create a space for all girls who ball to find joy in play, and feel seen, empowered and connected to a community — on and off the basketball court.
                            <!-- -->
                            <span>
                             <br/>
                            </span>
                            <span>
                             <br/>
                            </span>
                            <!-- -->
                            Beginning in 2021, Nike partnered with
                            <span class="white-space-pre">
                            </span>
                            <a class="app-aware-link" data-test-app-aware-link="" href="https://www.linkedin.com/company/dick%27s-sporting-goods/" target="_self">
                             <span>
                              <span>
                               <!-- -->
                               DICK'S Sporting Goods
                               <!-- -->
                              </span>
                             </span>
                            </a>
                            <span class="white-space-pre">
                            </span>
                            (DSG) to create “It’s Her Shot,” an experience that hosts hundreds of young girls for games, clinics and programs. The beauty of this partnership, says
                            <span class="white-space-pre">
                            </span>
                            <a class="app-aware-link" data-test-app-aware-link="" href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/ACoAAACsGKkBveMxreFmvelL_ZWzYQznq3eXPC4" target="_self">
                             <span>
                              <a class="ember-view" href="/in/mindy-helmer/" id="ember1643">
                               <!-- -->
                               Mindy Helmer
                               <!-- -->
                              </a>
                             </span>
                            </a>
                            <!-- -->
                            , is in the shared values. The Nike Director of Partner Marketing helps lead conversations between Nike and DSG on how sport can, and should, leave a positive impact on everyone, especially girls.
                            <!-- -->
                            <span>
                             <br/>
                            </span>
                            <span>
                             <br/>
                            </span>
                            <!-- -->
                            “One of the special parts about working at Nike is getting to work across so many different groups to do a project,” says Helmer, who’s been in the job for nearly three years. “From Social &amp; Community Impact to Communications to Sports Marketing, everyone involved in the program is just as passionate as I am about giving these girls an incredible experience and a newfound community through sport. This project has been a culmination of everything I’ve believed in during my 13-year Nike career about helping young girls find a sense of belonging.”
                            <!-- -->
                            <span>
                             <br/>
                            </span>
                            <span>
                             <br/>
                            </span>
                            <!-- -->
                            And it's not the only example. Learn more about Nike’s unique partnership to help build body confidence in girls:
                            <span class="white-space-pre">
                            </span>
                            <a class="app-aware-link" data-test-app-aware-link="" href="https://lnkd.in/ewJ3WRNY" target="_self">
                             <!-- -->
                             https://lnkd.in/ewJ3WRNY
                             <!-- -->
                            </a>
                            <span>
                             <br/>
                            </span>
                            <span>
                             <br/>
                            </span>
                            <a class="app-aware-link" data-test-app-aware-link="" href="https://www.linkedin.com/feed/hashtag/?keywords=swooshlife&amp;highlightedUpdateUrns=urn%3Ali%3Aactivity%3A7162879326483402752">
                             <span class="visually-hidden">
                              hashtag
                             </span>
                             <span>
                              <span aria-hidden="true">
                               #
                              </span>

                           <span dir="ltr">
                            <!-- -->
                            Welcome to the next era of Nike Air: the Nike Air Max Dn
                            <!-- -->
                            <span>
                             <br/>
                            </span>
                            <span>
                             <br/>
                            </span>
                            <!-- -->
                            It's different than any Nike Air creation you’ve ever seen. And thanks to Dynamic Air, it feels different too. The Nike Air Max Dn's new dual-pressure Air unit allows air to respond to pressure from each step, delivering a smooth sensation that isn’t just comfortable — it’s interactive. Leave it to the team at Nike to reinvent Air for a new generation.
                            <!-- -->
                            <span>
                             <br/>
                            </span>
                            <span>
                             <br/>
                            </span>
                            <!-- -->
                            “Dynamic Air raises our benchmark for what Nike Air feels like,” says
                            <span class="white-space-pre">
                            </span>
                            <a class="app-aware-link" data-test-app-aware-link="" href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/ACoAAAD-CWMBCSKTErGxFnixpZVwbQQBpwes47k" target="_self">
                             <span>
                              <a class="ember-view" href="/in/gomezkathy/" id="ember1674">
                               <!-- -->
                               Kathy Gomez
                               <!-- -->
                              </a>
                             </span>
                            </a>
                            <!-- -->
                            , Nike VP, NXT Footwear. “We’re always raising our expectations of what we can deliver for athletes. We’re using every tool at our disposal and every bit of our expertise to create new sensations with Air, while doing it more precisely. That expertise is where our teammates were so important in creating the Dn. Everyone from our researchers to our engineers to our material developers at Nike played a role is raising our standard for what’s possible with Air.”
                            <!-- -->
                            <span>
                             <br/>
                            </span>
                            <span>
                             <br/>
                            </span>

                         <div class="artdeco-dropdown artdeco-dropdown--placement-bottom artdeco-dropdown--justification-right ember-view" id="ember1610">
                          <button aria-expanded="false" aria-label="Open control menu for post by Nike" class="feed-shared-control-menu__trigger artdeco-button artdeco-button--tertiary artdeco-button--muted artdeco-button--1 artdeco-button--circle artdeco-dropdown__trigger artdeco-dropdown__trigger--placement-bottom ember-view" id="ember1611" tabindex="0" type="button">

                       <div class="feed-shared-update-v2__description-wrapper mr2" style="" tabindex="-1">
                        <div class="feed-shared-inline-show-more-text feed-shared-update-v2__description feed-shared-inline-show-more-text--minimal-padding feed-shared-inline-show-more-text--3-lines" tabindex="-1">
                         <div class="update-components-text relative update-components-update-v2__commentary" dir="ltr">
                          <!-- -->
                          <span class="break-words tvm-parent-container">
                           <!-- -->
                           <span dir="ltr">
                            <!-- -->
                            We observe January 15 as a National Day of Service, closing our U.S.-based Nike, Jordan and Converse offices, distribution centers and Air MI facilities. As Nike athletes, we know the intersection of civil rights and social justice isn’t passive, but participatory. This year, Nike is also celebrating its four-year milestone of the Black Community Commitment (BCC). Launched in 2020, Nike committed $40 million over four years, and Jordan Brand and Michael Jordan committed $100 million over 10 years, together investing in and supporting organizations focused on economic empowerment, education innovation and social justice to address racial inequality for the Black Community in the United States.
                            <!-- -->
                            <span>
                             <br/>
                            </span>
                            <span class="white-space-pre">
                            </span>
                            <!-- -->
                            <!-- -->
                            <span>
                             <br/>
                            </span>
                            <!-- -->
                            The BCC Task Force visited Memphis last fall to tour the National Civil Rights Museum, which Nike has supported since 1996, and Nike’s North America Logistics Campus (You can watch some footage of their visit below). The Task Force took the opportunity to speak directly with local Nike teammates and some of the local community organizations that have received BCC grants so far. This is how the success of the BCC must be measured, says Willie Gregory, Nike Sr. Director of Community Relations, Mid-South — by the health of these local organizations who are committed over the long haul to advance racial equity for Black Americans.
                            <!-- -->
                            <span>
                             <br/>
                            </span>
                            <span>
                             <br/>
                            </span>
                            <!-- -->
                            “If you’re a company, you owe your community the best you can give it,” says Gregory, who's also a BCC Task Force Member. “The BCC shows how Nike is helping the lead the way among companies that are making local communities better. I was born and raised in the city of Memphis. Nike is unique in how it encourages its employees to volunteer to this degree, allowing them to bank volunteer hours that can then be given as donations to the nonprofit of their choice. Making communities better must be a long-term, collaborative effort. That’s the spirit behind the BCC, and that’s the spirit among our employees.”
                            <!-- -->
                            <span>
                             <br/>
                            </span>
                            <span>
                             <br/>
                            </span>
                            <a class="app-aware-link" data-test-app-aware-link="" href="https://www.linkedin.com/feed/hashtag/?keywords=nikeblackcommunitycommitment&amp;highlightedUpdateUrns=urn%3Ali%3Aactivity%3A7152705097062322176">
                             <span class="visually-hidden">
                              hashtag
                             </span>
                             <span>
                              <span aria-hidden="true">
                               #
                              </span>
                              NikeBlackCommunityCommitment
                             </span>
                            </a>
                            <span class="white-space-pre">
                            </span>
                            <!-- -->
                            <!-- -->
                            <a class="app-aware-link" data-test-app-aware-link="" href="https://www.linkedin.com/feed/hashtag/?keywords=bcc&amp;highlightedUpdateUrns=urn%3Ali%3Aactivity%3A7152705097062322176">
                             <span class="visually-hidden">
                              hashtag
                             </span>
                             <span>
                              <span aria-hidden="true">
                               #
                              </span>

                           <span dir="ltr">
                            <!-- -->
                            Summer interns, that’s a wrap! Each year, the NIKE Internship Program is proud to welcome a diverse group of standout students to NIKE, Inc. offices. While we've said goodbye to our U.S. interns, we’re excited to welcome interns to our European offices this month. Applying their talents to a variety of fields across Nike, Jordan and Converse, our interns make a real impact for our business, receive mentorship, and ultimately, help us shape the future of sport. Check out the snapshot below of how our summer U.S. interns made NIKE, Inc. even better.
                            <!-- -->
                            <span>
                             <br/>
                            </span>
                            <span class="white-space-pre">
                            </span>
                            <!-- -->
                            <!-- -->
                            <span>
                             <br/>
                            </span>
                            <!-- -->
                            Sound like a company you want to be a part of? We’re accepting internship applications for our 2024 U.S. program now. Rising juniors have until October 9 to apply and first-year MBA students should apply by December 3:
                            <span class="white-space-pre">
                            </span>
                            <a class="app-aware-link" data-test-app-aware-link="" href="https://lnkd.in/d-iK3aT" target="_self">
                             <!-- -->

                          <!-- -->
                          <span class="break-words tvm-parent-container">
                           <!-- -->
                           <span dir="ltr">
                            <!-- -->
                            New parents are some of the hardest working athletes around, and when you’re a new parent on our team, we want to make sure you have the time you need to care for your family.
                            <!-- -->
                            <span>
                             <br/>
                            </span>
                            <span class="white-space-pre">
                            </span>
                            <!-- -->
                            <!-- -->
                            <span>
                             <br/>
                            </span>
                            <!-- -->
                            That’s why, as of June 1, we’ve doubled our parental leave benefit from 8 to 16 weeks for all U.S.-based NIKE, Inc. employees — including, for the first time, part-time retail teammates — to give them more time with their child after birth, adoption or foster placement.
                            <span class="white-space-pre">
                            </span>
                            <span>
                             <br/>
                            </span>
                            <span class="white-space-pre">
                            </span>
                            <!-- -->
                            <!-- -->
                            <span>
                             <br/>
                            </span>
                            <!-- -->
                            For first-time mom
                            <span class="white-space-pre">
                            </span>
                            <a class="app-aware-link" data-test-app-aware-link="" href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/ACoAAC1F9FwBcdKuJWa9u3nmbuK9zMzyNB3PeaU" target="_self">
                             <span>
                              <a class="ember-view" href="/in/kittorra-stokes-91045b192/" id="ember1915">
                               <!-- -->
                               Kittorra Stokes
                               <!-- -->
                              </a>
                             </span>
                            </a>
                            <!-- -->
                            , a Nike retail athlete who’s expecting twin girls later this summer, this best-in-class benefit gives personal and professional peace of mind.
                            <!-- -->
                            <span>
                             <br/>
                            </span>
                            <span class="white-space-pre">
                            </span>
                            <!-- -->
                            <!-- -->
                            <span>
                             <br/>
                            </span>
                            <!-- -->
                            “With two babies on the way, knowing that I’ll have 16 weeks of paid time to bond with them is such a blessing,” says Kittorra, who’s a part-time administrative assistant at Nike Chicago. “I think this benefit shows how much Nike cares about and supports its people — I know, for me, it reaffirmed why I work here and why I want to stay.”
                            <!-- -->
                            <span>
                             <br/>
                            </span>
                            <span class="white-space-pre">
                            </span>

                            We’re out to support parents with our products too; check out this behind-the-scenes look at how our Nike designers are creating better footwear and apparel for expecting and new moms:
                            <span class="white-space-pre">

                         <div class="artdeco-dropdown artdeco-dropdown--placement-bottom artdeco-dropdown--justification-right ember-view" id="ember1851">
                          <button aria-expanded="false" aria-label="Open control menu for post by Nike" class="feed-shared-control-menu__trigger artdeco-button artdeco-button--tertiary artdeco-button--muted artdeco-button--1 artdeco-button--circle artdeco-dropdown__trigger artdeco-dropdown__trigger--placement-bottom ember-view" id="ember1852" tabindex="0" type="button">

                       <!-- -->
                       <div class="feed-shared-update-v2__description-wrapper mr2" style="" tabindex="-1">
                        <div class="feed-shared-inline-show-more-text feed-shared-update-v2__description feed-shared-inline-show-more-text--minimal-padding feed-shared-inline-show-more-text--3-lines" tabindex="-1">
                         <div class="update-components-text relative update-components-update-v2__commentary" dir="ltr">
                          <!-- -->
                          <span class="break-words tvm-parent-container">
                           <!-- -->
                           <span dir="ltr">
                            <!-- -->
                            When Nike’s employee networks mobilize around a cause, they create change that ripples from the inside out.
                            <!-- -->
                            <span>
                             <br/>
                            </span>
                            <span>
                             <br/>
                            </span>
                            <!-- -->
                            That concept is nothing new for
                            <span class="white-space-pre">
                            </span>
                            <a class="app-aware-link" data-test-app-aware-link="" href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/ACoAAAlkVLABj9JWmcSz5pQVzzA6BZr1ST0797k" target="_self">
                             <span>
                              <a class="ember-view" href="/in/taya-saxton-58092a44/" id="ember1854">
                               <!-- -->
                               Taya Saxton
                               <!-- -->
                              </a>
                             </span>
                            </a>
                            <!-- -->
                            , a Director of Cross Functional Sustainability at Nike. Taya served over four years in the Air Force, and she’s worked at Nike for almost a decade now, helping lead the company’s supply chain strategy to become more environmentally responsible. As a member of the leadership team on Nike’s Military Veterans and Friends Network (NMV), Saxton and her colleagues saw another opportunity to spearhead: helping shape a paid leave program for Nike’s military employees.
                            <!-- -->
                            <span>
                             <br/>
                            </span>
                            <span>
                             <br/>
                            </span>
                            <!-- -->
                            “A consistent trait among our military friends is the resolve to find a way, even if you don’t know something,” says Taya. “When I was on active duty in the Air Force, I was immediately placed in an aerospace program. I knew nothing about satellites. But I didn’t have another option. I needed to hunker down and start learning. You find that commitment inside of every Nike military veteran.”
                            <!-- -->
                            <span>
                             <br/>
                            </span>
                            <span>
                             <br/>
                            </span>
                            <!-- -->
                            The network drafted a detailed proposal for the leave program in 2017, eventually presenting to the company’s senior leadership. The support was resounding. A year later, Nike introduced its military leave program, giving employees who volunteer or are called back to the uniformed services up to 12 weeks of paid time off every 12 months.
                            <!-- -->
                            <span>
                             <br/>
                            </span>
                            <span>
                             <br/>
                            </span>
                            <!-- -->
                            “The NMV really helped champion the program,” says Taya. “I love how our network gets to focus on showing up for the Nike military community at large, in addition to representing the military experience for all of our employees.”
                            <!-- -->
                            <span>
                             <br/>
                            </span>
                            <span>
                             <br/>
                            </span>
                            <!-- -->
                            Learn more about how Nike supports the personal and professional well-being of our employees:

                            </span>
                            <a class="app-aware-link" data-test-app-aware-link="" href="https://lnkd.in/dpWnGc33" target="_self">
                             <!-- -->
                             https://lnkd.in/dpWnGc33
                             <!-- -->
                            </a>

                            </span>

                       <div class="feed-shared-update-v2__description-wrapper mr2" style="" tabindex="-1">
                        <div class="feed-shared-inline-show-more-text feed-shared-update-v2__description feed-shared-inline-show-more-text--minimal-padding feed-shared-inline-show-more-text--3-lines" tabindex="-1">
                         <div class="update-components-text relative update-components-update-v2__commentary" dir="ltr">
                          <!-- -->
                          <span class="break-words tvm-parent-container">
                           <!-- -->
                           <span dir="ltr">
                            <!-- -->
                            We believe girls are the future of sport, the future of our brand and the future of our business. And we know that propelling girls to the forefront of sport will make it more inclusive, inviting and accessible to all.
                            <!-- -->
                            <span>
                             <br/>
                            </span>
                            <span class="white-space-pre">
                            </span>
                            <!-- -->
                            <!-- -->
                            <span>
                             <br/>
                            </span>
                            <!-- -->
                            That’s how “You Got This” was born. This YouTube series for 10- to 13-year-old girls is focused on vulnerable yet empowering conversations among adolescent girls, athletes and creators that illuminate how sports can help you find your confidence and true self as you grow up. We hope it shows the power of our commitment at Nike.
                            <span class="white-space-pre">
                            </span>
                            <span>
                             <br/>
                            </span>
                            <span>
                             <br/>
                            </span>
                            <!-- -->
                            “The momentum and energy behind women and girls in sport is phenomenal, and I feel incredibly honored to be in this change-making role at this time,” says
                            <span class="white-space-pre">
                            </span>
                            <a class="app-aware-link" data-test-app-aware-link="" href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/ACoAAAKaRIcBRfSVuxQyYCUYqEMt4pU5-ZaxAkA" target="_self">
                             <span>
                              <a class="ember-view" href="/in/stephanie-ankrah-99b75812/" id="ember1733">
                               <!-- -->
                               Stephanie Ankrah
                               <!-- -->
                              </a>
                             </span>
                            </a>
                            <!-- -->
                            , VP, Nike Kids Global Brand Management. “Having grown up playing sport, I have benefitted from the physical, emotional and mental power it gives you. And being part of a team who are supporting girls to be inspired to be in and stay in sport drives a huge internal purpose and passion for myself and the whole team. We want all girls to feel and experience the power of playing sport to build a lifetime of confidence.”
                            <!-- -->
                            <span>
                             <br/>
                            </span>
                            <span>
                             <br/>
                            </span>
                            <!-- -->
                            Check out the video to launch “You Got This” — and find out more about how we’re supporting girls and women in sport here:
                            <span class="white-space-pre">
                            </span>
                            <a class="app-aware-link" data-test-app-aware-link="" href="https://lnkd.in/g9uvxc8F" target="_self">

                       <div class="feed-shared-update-v2__description-wrapper mr2" style="" tabindex="-1">

                          <!-- -->
                          <span class="break-words tvm-parent-container">
                           <!-- -->
                           <span dir="ltr">
                            <!-- -->
                            At Nike, community is an open invitation. Our eight NikeUNITED employee-led networks are a huge part of that, and invite in all teammates, whether or not they directly identify with the network’s background. This month, Nike’s Ascend Network is organizing a packed week at our World Headquarters in Beaverton, Ore., including a block party and a cricket clinic, teaching the fundamentals of one of the world’s most popular sports. The Ascend Network includes teammates with roots in Asia, the Middle East and the Pacific Islands, and any Nike employee can join the celebration.
                            <!-- -->
                            <span>
                             <br/>
                            </span>
                            <span class="white-space-pre">
                            </span>
                            <!-- -->
                            <!-- -->
                            <span>
                             <br/>
                            </span>
                            <!-- -->
                            That impact is far reaching. Take it from
                            <span class="white-space-pre">
                            </span>
                            <a class="app-aware-link" data-test-app-aware-link="" href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/ACoAAAXo0J8BeZfWP5W11McLh2C8eXGN6GHefHU" target="_self">
                             <span>
                              <a class="ember-view" href="/in/kimej/" id="ember1823">
                               <!-- -->
                               EJ Kim
                               <!-- -->
                              </a>
                             </span>
                            </a>
                            <!-- -->
                            , a Senior Merchant for Global Men's Running Footwear at Nike, who wants all employees to know they can find a new, supportive community in Ascend.
                            <!-- -->
                            <span>
                             <br/>
                            </span>
                            <span class="white-space-pre">
                            </span>
                            <!-- -->
                            <!-- -->
                            <span>
                             <br/>
                            </span>
                            <!-- -->
                            “I’m grateful to be part of the Ascend Network in a leadership capacity and be able to organize events that celebrate and bring awareness to our diverse cultures,” says EJ. “I’ve had the opportunity to show up as my most authentic self at Nike. Our network encourages and inspires others in our community to do the same.”
                            <!-- -->
                            <span>

                            </span>
                            <span class="white-space-pre">
                            </span>

                          <span class="break-words tvm-parent-container">

                           <span dir="ltr">
                            <!-- -->
                            The disability experience is the human experience.
                            <span class="white-space-pre">
                            </span>
                            <span>
                             <br/>
                            </span>
                            <span class="white-space-pre">
                            </span>

                            <!-- -->
                            <span>
                             <br/>
                            </span>
                            <!-- -->
                            With that belief, we’re celebrating Global Accessibility Awareness Day with our Accessibility Center of Excellence and the Employee Disability Network proudly co-hosting our second annual Accessibility Summit, a two-day event on Nike’s World Headquarters campus in Beaverton, Ore.
                            <!-- -->
                            <span>
                             <br/>
                            </span>
                            <span>
                             <br/>
                            </span>
                            <!-- -->
                            At NIKE, Inc., the Accessibility Summit provides opportunity and space to build community, support teammates and demonstrate how accessibility has been and will continue to be a sharp point of innovation in product and in the employee experience.
                            <span class="white-space-pre">
                            </span>
                            <span>
                             <br/>
                            </span>
                            <span>
                             <br/>
                            </span>
                            <!-- -->
                            “Nike’s culture of innovation is fueled by curiosity and gaining insights from a diverse disability perspective to create the future of access to sport, fashion and self-expression for all," says
                            <span class="white-space-pre">
                            </span>
                            <a class="app-aware-link" data-test-app-aware-link="" href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/ACoAAAPk6r8BF7aNQ75vxIjiNGfv-ZOathzguV0" target="_self">

                               <!-- -->
                              </a>
                             </span>
                            </a>
                            <!-- -->
                            , Sr. Director of Global Accessibility and the host for the summit. “Nike is a company that values diverse ways of thinking and new ideas to drive innovation through the lens of inclusion.”
                            <!-- -->
                            <span>
                             <br/>
                            </span>
                            <span>

                           <span dir="ltr">
                            <!-- -->
                            Today marks 10 years of Air Max Day, and to celebrate, we’re sharing the behind-the-scenes story of creating the boldest look Max has seen in decades: the Nike Air Max Dn.
                            <!-- -->
                            <span>
                             <br/>
                            </span>
                            <span>
                             <br/>
                            </span>
                            <!-- -->
                            “For us, it meant going back to the roots of Air,” says Nike Product Director
                            <span class="white-space-pre">
                            </span>
                            <a class="app-aware-link" data-test-app-aware-link="" href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/ACoAAAVS17cBe0NdG51rcn9obVA3PSo4Yzv2m6E" target="_self">
                             <span>
                              <a class="ember-view" href="/in/reggie-hunter-09bab325/" id="ember1970">
                               <!-- -->
                               Reggie Hunter
                               <!-- -->
                              </a>
                             </span>
                            </a>
                            <!-- -->
                            , who helped lead the team that reimagined the platform. “I think what made Air Max originally so special was that it was developed for performance running, and those shoes felt responsive and were low to the ground. They looked fast, sleek, sophisticated. We wanted to revive this look and feel — and that was how the Nike Air Max Dn was born.”
                            <!-- -->
                            <span>
                             <br/>
                            </span>
                            <span>
                             <br/>
                            </span>
                            <!-- -->

                            </span>

                             <!-- -->
                             https://lnkd.in/gc9HS7k6
                             <!-- -->
                            </a>
                            <span>
                             <br/>
                            </span>
                            <span>
                             <br/>
                            </span>

                         <button aria-label="Follow Nike" class="follow update-components-actor__follow-button update-components-update-v2__follow-button artdeco-button update-components-update-v2__cta-button--next-to-control-menu artdeco-button--tertiary" type="button">

                         <div class="artdeco-dropdown artdeco-dropdown--placement-bottom artdeco-dropdown--justification-right ember-view" id="ember2167">
                          <button aria-expanded="false" aria-label="Open control menu for post by Nike" class="feed-shared-control-menu__trigger artdeco-button artdeco-button--tertiary artdeco-button--muted artdeco-button--1 artdeco-button--circle artdeco-dropdown__trigger artdeco-dropdown__trigger--placement-bottom ember-view" id="ember2168" tabindex="0" type="button">
                           <svg aria-hidden="true" class="artdeco-button__icon" data-supported-dps="16x16" data-test-icon="overflow-web-ios-small" height="16" role="none" viewbox="0 0 16 16" width="16" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg">

                       <!-- -->
                       <div class="feed-shared-update-v2__description-wrapper mr2" style="" tabindex="-1">
                        <div class="feed-shared-inline-show-more-text feed-shared-update-v2__description feed-shared-inline-show-more-text--minimal-padding feed-shared-inline-show-more-text--3-lines" tabindex="-1">
                         <div class="update-components-text relative update-components-update-v2__commentary" dir="ltr">
                          <!-- -->
                          <span class="break-words tvm-parent-container">
                           <!-- -->
                           <span dir="ltr">
                            <!-- -->
                            As a senior engineer with Nike’s Air Manufacturing Innovation (Air MI) team,
                            <span class="white-space-pre">
                            </span>
                            <a class="app-aware-link" data-test-app-aware-link="" href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/ACoAAA4J7aMBRg9GzppkKyegz7OOc3TrXY-Z5wQ" target="_self">
                             <span>
                              <a class="ember-view" href="/in/kristinanardoni/" id="ember2170">
                               <!-- -->
                               Kristina Nardoni
                               <!-- -->
                              </a>
                             </span>
                            </a>
                            <span class="white-space-pre">
                            </span>
                            is sworn to secrecy. That’s because she’s at the forefront of Air Bag manufacturing that will appear on Nike’s newest shoes, like the ones you’ll see this summer.
                            <!-- -->
                            <span>
                             <br/>
                            </span>
                            <span class="white-space-pre">
                            </span>
                            <!-- -->
                            <!-- -->
                            <span>
                             <br/>
                            </span>
                            <!-- -->
                            She started at Nike in 2017. Previously, her jobs had been in process engineering related to high-voltage equipment. A mentor told her about an opening for a Nike industrial engineering position out of the Air MI facility in Saint Charles, MO. Seven years later, she is using her experience to help launch new products and continue to improve Air Bags that have been beloved for years.
                            <!-- -->
                            <span>
                             <br/>
                            </span>
                            <span class="white-space-pre">
                            </span>
                            <!-- -->
                            <!-- -->
                            <span>
                             <br/>
                            </span>
                            <!-- -->
                            “Industrial engineers are working from a zoomed-out place thinking about a system at large,” says Nardoni. “Some people are most concerned about the Air Bag being used. Others are interested in the machines. We get to look the whole system. One example was when we modified a machine on the floor that was giving operators shoulder pain. We saw the problem and saw that the shoulder pain was symptomatic of something else.”
                            <!-- -->
                            <span>
                             <br/>
                            </span>
                            <span class="white-space-pre">
                            </span>
                            <!-- -->
                            <!-- -->
                            <span>
                             <br/>
                            </span>
                            <!-- -->
                            Nardoni’s deep look at the whole system is also her filter for seeing the holistic development of her own skills. Through Nike’s tuition reimbursement program, Krissy is earning her master's degree in management. She's taking a class at a time, and if she earns an A or a B, she gets reimbursed for the class. “I’m paying just a couple hundred bucks a year to get my master’s degree when it could be costing me thousands,” she says.
                            <!-- -->
                            <span>
                             <br/>
                            </span>
                            <span class="white-space-pre">
                            </span>
                            <!-- -->
                            <!-- -->
                            <span>
                             <br/>
                            </span>
                            <!-- -->
                            Krissy has added to her Nike experience in more ways than just her rising job title. She also served as executive chairwoman of the Women of Nike (WON) employee network. She brought her zoomed-out POV to the position. For example, WON wanted to provide a delicious lunch to Air MI employees who worked nontraditional schedules. So, the team celebrated a midnight cookout together.
                            <!-- -->
                            <span>
                             <br/>
                            </span>
                            <span class="white-space-pre">
                            </span>
                            <!-- -->
                            <!-- -->
                            <span>
                             <br/>
                            </span>
                            <!-- -->
                            Her advice to Nike employees: Learn as much as you can. Take advantage of the learning programs that are offered at the company. Be a sponge. “If you see a maintenance technician fixing a chiller at your workplace, ask what they’re working on,” she says. “You never know what you might learn.”
                            <!-- -->
                            <span>
                             <br/>
                            </span>
                            <span>
                             <br/>
                            </span>
                            <a class="app-aware-link" data-test-app-aware-link="" href="https://www.linkedin.com/feed/hashtag/?keywords=nikeairmi&amp;highlightedUpdateUrns=urn%3Ali%3Aactivity%3A7171542742672531456">
                             <span class="visually-hidden">
                              hashtag
                             </span>
                             <span>
                              <span aria-hidden="true">
                               #
                              </span>

                             </span>
                            </a>
                            <span class="white-space-pre">
                            </span>
                            <!-- -->
                            <!-- -->

                             <span class="visually-hidden">

                  <div class="full-height">
                   <div class="feed-shared-update-v2 feed-shared-update-v2--minimal-padding full-height relative feed-shared-update-v2--e2e artdeco-card" data-urn="urn:li:activity:7165763765655814147" id="ember2071" role="region">

                     <div role="status">

                     </div>
                     <div class="display-flex flex-column flex-grow-1">
                      <h2 class="visually-hidden">
                       Feed post number 69
                      </h2>
                      <div id="fie-impression-container">

Employees also got an exclusive, first-look screening of “Giannis: The Marvelous Journey,” which released yesterday on major streaming platforms.

                       <div class="feed-shared-update-v2__description-wrapper mr2" style="" tabindex="-1">
                        <div class="feed-shared-inline-show-more-text feed-shared-update-v2__description feed-shared-inline-show-more-text--minimal-padding feed-shared-inline-show-more-text--3-lines" tabindex="-1">
                         <div class="update-components-text relative update-components-update-v2__commentary" dir="ltr">
                          <!-- -->
                          <span class="break-words tvm-parent-container">
                           <!-- -->
                           <span dir="ltr">
                            <!-- -->
                            What’s better than a Nike store opening? One that kicks off with the help of NewJeans. This past Saturday, Nike welcomed the all-female group for their first-ever performance in Singapore to celebrate the opening of Nike Orchard Road, the city’s newest sports hub.
                            <!-- -->
                            <span>
                             <br/>
                            </span>
                            <span class="white-space-pre">
                            </span>
                            <!-- -->
                            <!-- -->
                            <span>
                             <br/>
                            </span>
                            <!-- -->
                            “Having NewJeans at Nike Orchard Road wasn’t just exciting, it was _beyond_,” says
                            <span class="white-space-pre">
                            </span>
                            <a class="app-aware-link" data-test-app-aware-link="" href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/ACoAAAfS7pEBoL8KhK7wCnBkGN-4C4cC3a6JyGA" target="_self">
                             <span>
                              <a class="ember-view" href="/in/dianna-tai/" id="ember2015">
                               <!-- -->
                               Dianna Tai
                               <!-- -->
                              </a>
                             </span>
                            </a>
                            <!-- -->
                            , Nike Catalyst Brand Manager, SEA&amp;I. “This was their first performance at a Nike event, and the energy and response from our consumers was amazing.”
                            <!-- -->
                            <span>
                             <br/>
                            </span>
                            <span class="white-space-pre">
                            </span>
                            <!-- -->
                            <!-- -->
                            <span>
                             <br/>
                            </span>
                            <!-- -->
                            The activation was also the first major cross-territory partnership between Nike SEA&amp;I and Nike Korea, Dianna says, and the teams pulled it off because of their shared dedication to invite more people into sport, especially women and girls.
                            <!-- -->
                            <span>
                             <br/>
                            </span>
                            <span class="white-space-pre">
                            </span>
                            <!-- -->
                            <!-- -->
                            <span>
                             <br/>
                            </span>
                            <!-- -->
                            “I cannot tell you how many times I’ve heard ‘I’ve got your back,’ ‘We’re in this together,’ and ‘Let’s do this!’ since I’ve joined Nike,” she says. “Beyond the work itself, it is so important and comforting to know that you belong to a team that’s unified in supporting each other, every step of the way.”
                            <!-- -->
                            <span>
                             <br/>
                            </span>
                            <span class="white-space-pre">
                            </span>
                            <!-- -->
                            <!-- -->
                            <span>
                             <br/>
                            </span>
                            <!-- -->
                            Learn more about the new Nike Orchard Road opening:
                            <span class="white-space-pre">
                            </span>

                         <div class="artdeco-dropdown artdeco-dropdown--placement-bottom artdeco-dropdown--justification-right ember-view" id="ember2043">
                          <button aria-expanded="false" aria-label="Open control menu for post by Nike" class="feed-shared-control-menu__trigger artdeco-button artdeco-button--tertiary artdeco-button--muted artdeco-button--1 artdeco-button--circle artdeco-dropdown__trigger artdeco-dropdown__trigger--placement-bottom ember-view" id="ember2044" tabindex="0" type="button">

                          <div aria-hidden="true" aria-label="Control Menu Options" class="feed-shared-control-menu__content artdeco-dropdown__content artdeco-dropdown--is-dropdown-element artdeco-dropdown__content--has-arrow artdeco-dropdown__content--arrow-right artdeco-dropdown__content--justification-right artdeco-dropdown__content--placement-bottom ember-view" id="ember2045" tabindex="-1">

                       <!-- -->
                       <div class="feed-shared-update-v2__description-wrapper mr2" style="" tabindex="-1">
                        <div class="feed-shared-inline-show-more-text feed-shared-update-v2__description feed-shared-inline-show-more-text--minimal-padding feed-shared-inline-show-more-text--3-lines" tabindex="-1">
                         <div class="update-components-text relative update-components-update-v2__commentary" dir="ltr">
                          <!-- -->
                          <span class="break-words tvm-parent-container">
                           <!-- -->
                           <span dir="ltr">
                            <!-- -->
                            “There are all kinds of achievements we can work toward in running — and life — and this group embraced and celebrated them all.”
                            <!-- -->
                            <span>
                             <br/>
                            </span>
                            <span>
                             <br/>
                            </span>
                            <!-- -->
                            That’s
                            <span class="white-space-pre">
                            </span>
                            <a class="app-aware-link" data-test-app-aware-link="" href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/ACoAAA1fpd4BvNNttboCbl8Nt3uc7aFBsZhT5Vw" target="_self">
                             <span>
                              <a class="ember-view" href="/in/allieschaich/" id="ember2046">
                               <!-- -->
                               Allie Schaich
                               <!-- -->
                              </a>
                             </span>
                            </a>
                            <!-- -->
                            , one of 120 women across the United States who made up Nike’s Project Dreamweaver, a program created to help athletes chase their dreams of qualifying for the most competitive U.S. Olympic Marathon Trials ever assembled.
                            <!-- -->
                            <span>
                             <br/>
                            </span>
                            <span>
                             <br/>
                            </span>
                            <!-- -->
                            Nike listened as everyday marathoners questioned if the new Women’s Olympic Trials Qualification (OTQ) of 2:37 — a drop of eight minutes from the 2020 Trials — could be done. The Nike team quickly pulled together the resources, expertise and community to help them.
                            <!-- -->
                            <span>
                             <br/>
                            </span>
                            <span>
                             <br/>
                            </span>
                            <!-- -->
                            Similar to Nike’s unparalleled support of its elite athlete roster, Project Dreamweaver offered program participants the holistic resources and help needed, from coaching and nutrition to sport psychology and physiology guidance and more. The partnership supported the athletes both in the renowned Nike Sport Research Lab and the roads where they trained and raced across the U.S over the last two years.
                            <!-- -->
                            <span>
                             <br/>
                            </span>
                            <span>
                             <br/>
                            </span>
                            <!-- -->
                            That support included creating a community of women who rallied each other forward, says Schaich, who works at Nike as a Manager in Strategy and Connected Membership. While Project Dreamweaver runners varied in skill levels, background and hometowns, they were united by a common belief: a dream worth pursuing is worth chasing together. When Schaich toes the starting line this weekend for the Trials in Orlando, she’ll have the collective behind her.
                            <!-- -->
                            <span>
                             <br/>
                            </span>
                            <span>
                             <br/>
                            </span>
                            <!-- -->
                            “Finding the time to train at the level I want to while working full-time isn’t easy, but being able to have great friends and coworkers I’ve met through this program by my side has made a huge difference," says Schaich. "I doubt there’s a remotely similar community out there that could provide the same level of support and excitement toward others achieving their goals — whether that was the OTQ, a PR, or just overcoming an injury and getting back into running after a hiatus.”
                            <!-- -->
                            <span>
                             <br/>
                            </span>
                            <span>
                             <br/>
                            </span>
                            <!-- -->
                            Learn more about Project Dreamweaver:
                            <span class="white-space-pre">
                            </span>
                            <a class="app-aware-link" data-test-app-aware-link="" href="https://lnkd.in/d79NDCEz" target="_self">
                             <!-- -->
                             https://lnkd.in/d79NDCEz
                             <!-- -->
                            </a>
                            <span>
                             <br/>
                            </span>
                            <span>
                             <br/>
                            </span>

                             </span>

                  <div class="full-height">
                   <div class="feed-shared-update-v2 feed-shared-update-v2--minimal-padding full-height relative feed-shared-update-v2--e2e artdeco-card" data-urn="urn:li:activity:7156338463682752512" id="ember2132" role="region">

                     <div class="display-flex flex-column flex-grow-1">
                      <h2 class="visually-hidden">
                       Feed post number 72
                      </h2>
                      <div id="fie-impression-container">
                       <!-- -->
                       <div class="relative">
                        <div class="update-components-actor display-flex update-components-actor--with-control-menu">

                       <!-- -->
                       <div class="feed-shared-update-v2__description-wrapper mr2" style="" tabindex="-1">
                        <div class="feed-shared-inline-show-more-text feed-shared-update-v2__description feed-shared-inline-show-more-text--minimal-padding feed-shared-inline-show-more-text--3-lines" tabindex="-1">
                         <div class="update-components-text relative update-components-update-v2__commentary" dir="ltr">
                          <!-- -->
                          <span class="break-words tvm-parent-container">
                           <!-- -->
                           <span dir="ltr">
                            <a class="app-aware-link" data-test-app-aware-link="" href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/ACoAAADCW34BZKwAQum0QZQ4fxuEaPXzZrlvXlE" target="_self">
                             <span>
                              <a class="ember-view" href="/in/tyler-faligowski-2263234/" id="ember2138">
                               <!-- -->
                               Tyler Faligowski
                               <!-- -->
                              </a>
                             </span>
                            </a>
                            <span class="white-space-pre">
                            </span>
                            has worked at Nike for more than 27 years. He’s held seven different titles in Air Manufacturing Innovation (Air MI), which creates the next generation of Air units for Nike shoes. He’s worked four different production floor shifts and worked in many different locations, including Nike’s World Headquarters (WHQ) in Beaverton, Ore. He always knew what his ultimate goal was from the minute he was hired in ‘95: to be a supervisor on the production floor at Air MI. Today, he's the leader he dreamed of becoming.
                            <!-- -->
                            <span>
                             <br/>
                            </span>
                            <span class="white-space-pre">
                            </span>
                            <!-- -->
                            <!-- -->
                            <span>
                             <br/>
                            </span>
                            <!-- -->
                            “It was back in ’99 when I was working in Nike Team Sports at WHQ, when one day, an old manager of mine at Air MI called me up,” says Tyler. “There was a weekend supervisor role at AIR Sole – that was the name of Air MI at the time. I applied for it and got it, so I went back to manufacturing. Having my former leader reach out to me was extremely rewarding. He saw potential in me, but more importantly, we had a genuine relationship that continued even after I left the team.”
                            <!-- -->
                            <span>
                             <br/>
                            </span>
                            <span>
                             <br/>
                            </span>
                            <!-- -->
                            Tyler was promoted to Production Manager in 2010 and then Director of Production Operations in 2017, leading different production platforms at Air MI.
                            <span class="white-space-pre">
                            </span>
                            <span>
                             <br/>
                            </span>
                            <span>
                             <br/>
                            </span>
                            <!-- -->
                            Today, he finds ways to pay it forward and advocate for his team like his former managers did for him. He helps lead a program at Air MI that empowers workers to share their voice with leadership and create positive change they want to see. Last year, Tyler worked with a team of operators on ideas to make job postings more visible and meeting agendas more transparent.
                            <!-- -->
                            <span>
                             <br/>
                            </span>
                            <span>
                             <br/>
                            </span>
                            <!-- -->
                            Through it all, it's the people who made him want to establish a lifelong, managerial career path at Nike.
                            <!-- -->
                            <span>
                             <br/>
                            </span>
                            <span>
                             <br/>
                            </span>
                            <!-- -->
                            “Connecting with people and helping them are big reasons why I wanted to advance at Nike,” says Tyler. “Becoming a leader was about helping create change with my teammates. Together. we’re making the company better.”
                            <!-- -->
                            <span>
                             <br/>
                            </span>
                            <span>
                             <br/>
                            </span>
                            <!-- -->
                            Sound like a company you want to work for? Go to
                            <span class="white-space-pre">
                            </span>

                       <!-- -->
                       <div class="feed-shared-update-v2__description-wrapper mr2" style="" tabindex="-1">
                        <div class="feed-shared-inline-show-more-text feed-shared-update-v2__description feed-shared-inline-show-more-text--minimal-padding feed-shared-inline-show-more-text--3-lines" tabindex="-1">
                         <div class="update-components-text relative update-components-update-v2__commentary" dir="ltr">
                          <!-- -->
                          <span class="break-words tvm-parent-container">
                           <!-- -->
                           <span dir="ltr">
                            <!-- -->
                            The Boston Celtics play the Denver Nuggets tomorrow in a battle of East against West. Even from the view on your couch, you’ll likely spot those distinct foam pods on the sides of Jayson Tatum’s second signature shoe with Jordan Brand, the Tatum 2. The shoe’s design is rooted in a philosophy that powers Jordan Brand’s approach to performance footwear: get at the motion and emotion behind Tatum’s game, and distill those qualities through every facet of the shoe.
                            <!-- -->
                            <span>
                             <br/>
                            </span>
                            <span>
                             <br/>
                            </span>
                            <!-- -->
                            For
                            <span class="white-space-pre">
                            </span>
                            <a class="app-aware-link" data-test-app-aware-link="" href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/ACoAABMHcFEBuNW1yptgmvaHj3vBj1CJH9npjRI" target="_self">
                             <span>
                              <a class="ember-view" href="/in/kelsey-%E2%80%9Cshme%E2%80%9D-amy-9a9b018a/" id="ember2107">
                               <!-- -->
                               Kelsey “Shme” Amy
                               <!-- -->
                              </a>
                             </span>
                            </a>
                            <!-- -->
                            , Expert Color Designer of Performance Footwear at Jordan Brand, color is her tool to tell Jayson’s story. She started working alongside the All-Star forward in 2019 with the Air Jordan XXXIV. Since then, they’ve worked on six different models together, brainstormed more than 100 colorways, and most important, have forged one solid relationship. It’s not uncommon for Amy to get a text from Jayson, day or night, about a wild new colorway idea. What does she think? Can the team make it happen? For Amy, professional trust from athletes like Jayson might be the single most important factor of her job — and one that she loves.
                            <!-- -->
                            <span>
                             <br/>
                            </span>
                            <span>
                             <br/>
                            </span>
                            <!-- -->
                            “Our whole team has established a relationship with Jayson where he lets us take a lot of big, bold swings in his shoe design,” says Kelsey. “Those big ideas come to life for me through color. Jayson has an open line of communication with us at any time, because we all want to make his ideas a reality. When you get an entire group who’s committed to growing that same level of trust with Jayson, you get a really special team, and a really special shoe.”
                            <span class="white-space-pre">
                            </span>
                            <span>
                             <br/>
                            </span>
                            <span>
                             <br/>
                            </span>
                            <!-- -->
